 daughter of  Henry I  of England (  see  Maud  ). The name was introduced into England by the Normans, and this Latinized form is the one that normally occurs in medieval records, while the vernacular form <i>Maud</i> was the one in everyday use. <i>Matilda</i> was revived in England as a learned form in the 18th century."],"variants":[{"name":"Mathilda","meanings":["Latinized form of a Germanic personal name derived from <i>maht</i>, <i>meht</i> ‘might’ + <i>hild</i> ‘battle’. This was the name of an early German queen (  895–968 ), wife of  Henry  the Fowler, who was noted for her piety and generosity. It was also the name of the wife of  William  the Conqueror and of the daughter of  Henry I  of England (  see  Maud  ). The name was introduced into England by the Normans, and this Latinized form is the one that normally occurs in medieval records, while the vernacular form <i>Maud</i> was the one in everyday use. <i>Matilda</i> was revived in England as a learned form in the 18th century."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Matilda FitzJoscelin was born about 1112, in Redbourne, Lincolnshire, England, United Kingdom as the daughter of Gilbert FitzJoscelin and Unknown. She married Reginald de Crèvecoeur in 1129, in Redbourne, Lincolnshire, England. They were the parents of at least 1 son. She died about 1170, in her hometown, at the age of 60."},"et":{"about 1112–about 1170":"umbes 1112–umbes 1170","1112–1170":"1112–1170","1098–1165":"1098–1165","1140–1164":"1140–1164","1087–1128":"1087–1128","–Female":"Surnud","about 1140":"umbes 1140","about 1170":"umbes 1170","1165":"1165","1087":"1087","1164":"1164","1098":"1098","1140":"1140","1170":"1170","1129":"1129","1128":"1128","1115":"1115","1112":"1112","about 1128":"umbes 1128","about 1112":"umbes 1112","after 1165":"pärast 1165","about 1164":"umbes 1164","Brigg, Lincolnshire, England":"Brigg, Lincolnshire, England","Redbourne, Lincolnshire, England":"Redbourne, Lincolnshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"about 1112–about 117